article.headline: Iverson scores five points, ends double figures streak
article.linkText: Easy street in Detroit as Pistons handle Sixers
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Pistons made Allen Iverson want to just go home.
 
Billups
Chauncey Billups scored 29 points as the Pistons beat the Philadelphia 76ers 113-85 Thursday night, and snapped Iverson's 186-game streak of scoring in double figures. Iverson scored just five points, his lowest output since scoring five points on March 2, 2000, against Washington. The Pistons held him to a career-low four points on March 23, 1998. Iverson -- who went just 2-for-11 before sitting out the fourth quarter -- averaged 32.1 points in the previous eight games. "I think that was one of the worst basketball experiences I ever had, especially from a personal standpoint and how I played," Iverson said. "It was just one that I'm ready to get out of my system. I'm just glad that I got the opportunity to try it all over again (Friday at home against Atlanta). "It was just one of those nights when you hope the game hurry up and get over. We can't wait to get home." The Eastern Conference-leading Pistons (43-24) won for the sixth time in seven games to move 2½ games ahead of New Jersey for the best record in the conference, and 3½ games ahead of Indiana in the Central Division. "We played one of our best games and obviously, Philly½ didn't," Detroit coach Rick Carlisle said. Philadelphia (40-27) had won 17 of 19 since the All-Star break coming into the game. Even with the loss, the 76ers are just a half-game behind New Jersey. "It hurts because it's a loss, simple as that," Iverson said. "We don't really care about (the standings). We just want to get wins, we don't care who they're against." Detroit's Ben Wallace scored eight points, blocked nine shots _ four against Iverson -- and grabbed 22 rebounds, surpassing the 20-rebound mark for the fifth straight game. He tied a team record, which he already shared, with seven blocks in the first half. If Wallace didn't come out of the game with 8:45 left, he may have earned his third career triple-double in points, rebounds and blocks. "My teammates were keeping me informed so I knew I was close to it," Wallace said. "I wanted to get the triple-double, but it was the right move to make." Billups is averaging 26.4 games in the nine games this month, and likely would've scored 30 for a fourth time this month if he wasn't taken out just before Wallace was. "Scoring is not my main objective," Billups said. "I'm looking to just run the team. But I'll take shots and if I get it going, I'm going to stay aggressive." The Pistons took control of the game for good when they closed the first quarter with a 16-5 run to take a 29-18 lead. They led 59-38 at halftime and 86-56 after three quarters. Detroit's Mehmet Okur scored 18, Richard Hamilton had 15, Corliss Williamson added 14 and Cliff Robinson and Chucky Atkins each scored 10. Atkins scored all of his points in the first half and did not return in the second half after re-aggravating the bone bruise in his left knee, which had him on the injured list from March 4 until Tuesday. "I'm not sure what his status will be for (Friday at New York)," Carlisle said. Philadelphia's Derrick Coleman continued his strong play with 19 points. Eric Snow scored 12. Game notes
The last time Iverson scored in single digits was Nov. 22, 2000, at Charlotte, when he scored seven. ... The 76ers' worst loss of the season was 98-69 at Utah on Dec. 28. ... The Pistons are 14-0 when scoring at least 100. ... Detroit leads the season series with the 76ers 2-1, and plays at Philadelphia on April 8. ... The Pistons play nine of their final 15 games at home. ... Brown said Thursday that Iverson belongs on the 2004 Olympic team, and is ``pretty confident it will work out for him.''
